# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: airsoft-pellets
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:airsoft-pellets/4-5-mm-caliber] The **.177 caliber** or **4.5 mm caliber** is the smallest diameter of pellets and BB shots widely used in air guns, and is the only caliber generally accepted for formal target competition.
[src:airsoft-pellets/4-5-mm-caliber] It is also sometimes used for hunting small game, like fowl.
[src:airsoft-pellets/4-5-mm-caliber] It is also used in field target competitions, where it competes with .20 caliber (5 mm) and .22 caliber (5.6 mm) rifles.
[src:airsoft-pellets/4-5-mm-caliber] Steel BBs are typically slightly smaller than lead BBs at 0.175-inch (4.4 mm) diameter, although the bore diameter of the barrel are the same.
[src:airsoft-pellets/4-5-mm-caliber] Some air guns are designed to accept .177 pellets, .177 lead shot, or .175 steel BBs interchangeably.
[src:airsoft-pellets/4-5-mm-caliber] If two guns fire pellets of different weights, the gun firing the lighter pellet must fire it at a higher velocity to achieve the same muzzle energy.
[src:airsoft-pellets/4-5-mm-caliber] This is an important consideration in locations where air guns are legally restricted by muzzle energy.
[src:airsoft-pellets/4-5-mm-caliber] Because a .177 pellet is lighter than a larger caliber pellet of similar design, the .177 pellet can be propelled faster and therefore on a flatter trajectory, without exceeding the legal limit on energy.
[src:airsoft-pellets/4-5-mm-caliber] However, because the lighter projectile has a lower ballistic coefficient, it loses its initial energy to air resistance faster than a heavier, slower pellet.
[src:airsoft-pellets/4-5-mm-caliber] Therefore, a heavier pellet (typically of a larger caliber) may be preferred for hunting.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] An **air gun** or **airgun** is a gun that uses compressed air or other pressurized gases to fire projectiles, reminiscent of the principle behind the ancient blowgun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] This is in contrast to a firearm, which shoots projectiles using pressure generated via combustion of a chemical propellant, most often black powder in antique firearms and smokeless powder in modern firearms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Air guns come in both long gun (**air rifle**) and handgun (**air pistol**) forms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Both types typically propel metallic projectiles that are either diabolo-shaped pellets or spherical shots called BBs, although in recent years Minié ball-shaped cylindro-conoidal projectiles called slugs are becoming more popular.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Certain types of air guns (usually air rifles) may also launch fin-stabilized projectile such as darts (e.g., tranquilizer guns) or hollow-shafted arrows (so-called "airbows").
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The air guns were first developed in the 16th century, and have since been used in hunting, shooting sports, and even in warfare.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] There are three different power sources for modern air guns, depending on the design: spring-piston, pneumatic or bottled compressed gas (most commonly carbon dioxide and recently nitrogen).
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Air guns represent the oldest pneumatic technology.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The oldest existing mechanical air gun dates back to about 1580, and is currently kept in the Livrustkammaren Museum in Stockholm.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] This is approximately what most historians recognize as the beginning of the modern air gun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Throughout 17th to 19th century, air guns in .30 to .51 calibers were used to hunt big game, deer and wild boar.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] These air rifles were charged using a pump to fill an air reservoir and produced velocities from 650 to 1,000 ft/s (200 to 300 m/s).
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] They were also used in warfare, the most recognized example being the Girandoni air rifle, a repeating rifle used by Austria in the 1788 war against Turkey.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] At that time, they had compelling advantages over the muzzleloader firearms of the day.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] For example, air guns could be discharged in wet weather and rain (unlike both matchlock and flintlock muskets), and discharged much faster than muzzle-loading guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Moreover, they were quieter than a firearm of a similar caliber and produced no muzzle flash or smoke cloud when fired.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Thus, they did not give away the shooter's position or obscure the shooter's view, unlike the black powder muskets of the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] In the hands of skilled soldiers, they gave the military a distinct advantage.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] France, Austria and other nations had special sniper detachments using air rifles, mostly Jäger (infantry).
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The Austrian 1779 model was named *Windbüchse* (literally "wind rifle" in German).
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The gun was developed in 1768 or 1769 by the Tyrolean Ladins watchmaker, mechanic and gunsmith Bartholomäus Girardoni (1744–1799) and is sometimes referred to as the Girandoni air rifle or Girardoni air gun in literature (the name is also spelled "Girandony", "Giradoni" or "Girardoni".).
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Adopted by the Austrian leadership in 1779, the *Windbüchse* was about 4 ft (1.2 m) long and weighed 10 pounds (4.5 kg), about the same size and mass as a conventional musket.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The air reservoir was a removable, club-shaped, butt.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The *Windbüchse* carried twenty-two .51 caliber (13 mm) lead balls in a tubular magazine.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] A skilled shooter could fire off one magazine in about thirty seconds.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] A shot from this air gun could penetrate a one-inch-thick (2.5 cm) wooden board at a hundred paces, an effect roughly equal to that of a modern 9×19mm or .45 ACP caliber pistol.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Circa 1820, the Japanese inventor Kunitomo Ikkansai developed various manufacturing methods for guns, and also created an air gun based on the study of Western knowledge ("rangaku") acquired from the Dutch in Dejima.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The Lewis and Clark Expedition (1804) carried a reservoir air gun, very likely the Girardoni, as it held 22 round balls of .46 caliber in a tubular magazine mounted on the side of the barrel.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The butt of the gun served as the air reservoir and had a working pressure of 800 psi (55 bar).
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The rifle was said to be capable of 22 aimed shots per minute and had a rifled bore of 0.452 in (11.5 mm) and a groove diameter 0.462 in (11.7 mm).
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] One of the first commercially successful and mass-produced air guns was manufactured by the William F.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Markham's Markham Air Rifle Company in Plymouth, Michigan, US.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Their first model air gun was the wooden *Challenger*, marketed in 1886.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] In response, Clarence Hamilton from the neighboring Plymouth Air Rifle Company (later renamed to Daisy Manufacturing Company in 1895) marketed their all-metal Daisy BB Gun in early 1888, which prompted Markham to respond with their *Chicago* model in 1888 followed by the *King* model in 1890.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The *Chicago* model was sold by Sears, Roebuck for 73 cents in its catalog.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] In 1928, the name of the Markham company was changed to King Air Rifle Company after the company was purchased by Daisy in 1916 after decades of intense competition, and continued to manufacture the "King" model air rifle until 1935 before ceasing operation altogether in the 1940s.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] From the 1890s onwards, air rifles were used in Birmingham, England for competitive target shooting.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Matches were held in public houses and working men's clubs, which sponsored shooting teams.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] This often took the form of Bell Target shooting, where the competitor aims to ring a bell by shooting through a small hole in a steel plate.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Prizes, such as a leg of mutton for the winning team, were paid for by the losing team.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] During this time, over 4,000 air rifle clubs and associations existed across Great Britain, with as many as 1,600 in Birmingham alone.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] During this time, the air gun was associated with poaching because it could deliver a shot without a significant muzzle report.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Air guns are used for hunting (small to medium game), pest control, recreational shooting (commonly known as plinking) and competitive sports such as the Olympic 10 m air rifle and 10 m air pistol events.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Field target (FT) is a competitive form of metallic silhouette shooting in which the targets are animal-shaped steel targets with a "kill zone" cut-out.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Hunter field target (HFT) is a variation, using identical equipment, but with differing rules.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The distances FT and HFT competitions are shot at range between 7.3 and 41.1 metres (24 and 135 ft) for HFT & 7.3 and 50.29 metres (24.0 and 165.0 ft) for FT, with varying sizes of "reducers" being used to increase or decrease the size of the kill zone.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] In the UK, competition power limits are set at the legal maximum for an unlicensed air rifle, i.e.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Air rifle benchrest is an international shooting sport where the objective is to hit a (small) bulls eye target at 25 m (27.34 yd) shooting distance.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] There are two divisions ARLV 12 ft⋅lbf (16.27 J) and ARHV 20 ft⋅lbf (27.12 J).
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The increasing affordability of higher-power pre-charged pneumatic (PCP) rifles has allowed large projectiles and further target distance for competition purposes.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] For instance, the Extreme Benchrest competition held annually in Green Valley, Arizona allows calibers up to .30 inches (7.6 mm) at 75 yd (68.58 m) while the Big Bore Benchrest arm of the same competition at other localities engages targets at 35 to 300 yards (32 to 274 m).
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The component of an airgun that provides the gas pressure needed to propel projectiles is called its *powerplant*, which uses internally stored pressurized gas; and *compressed gas* (most commonly CO2), which uses external sources of pressurized gas.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] A **spring-piston air gun** (also known as a **spring gun** or simply a "**springer**") operates by means of a spring-loaded piston pump assembly contained within a compression chamber separate from the gun barrel.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Traditionally, a grease-lubricated steel coil spring is used as the powerplant main spring.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Before shooting, the user needs to manually cock the gun by flexing a lever connected to the pump assembly, which pulls the pump piston rearwards and compresses the main spring until the rear of the piston engages the sear.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] When shooting, the trigger is pulled and disengages the sear, allowing the main spring to decompress and release its stored elastic potential energy, pushing the piston forward, thereby compressing the air in the pump cylinder.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] All this takes place in a fraction of a second, during which the air undergoes adiabatic heating to several hundred degrees and then cools as the air expands.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] This can also cause a phenomenon referred as "dieseling", where flammable substances in the compression chamber (e.g., petroleum-based lubricant) can be ignited by the compression heat like in a diesel engine, and lead to an afterburner effect with (often unpredictable) additional thrusts.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] This often results in combustion smoke coming out of the muzzle and potential pressure damage to the rubber O-ring seals inside the gun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Dieseling can be made to occur *intentionally* to increase power, by coating the pellet with lubricant or petroleum jelly, although this may result in damage to the breech seal.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Most spring-piston guns are single-shot breechloaders by nature, but multiple-shot repeaters with magazine feeders have been introduced in recent years by manufacturers such as Gamo, Umarex and Hatsan.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Spring-piston guns, especially the high-powered "magnum" guns, are able to achieve muzzle velocities exceeding the speed of sound.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The effort required for the cocking stroke is proportional to the designed power of the gun, with higher muzzle velocities requiring a stiffer spring and hence a greater cocking effort.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Spring-piston guns have a practical upper limit of 1,250 ft/s (380 m/s) for .177 cal (4.5 mm) pellets, as higher velocities cause unstable pellet flight and loss of accuracy.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] This is due to the extreme buffeting caused when the pellet reaches and surpasses transonic speed, then slows back down and goes through sound barrier again, which is more than enough to destabilize the pellet's flight.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Shortly after leaving the barrel, the supersonic pellet falls back below the speed of sound and the shock wave overtakes the pellet, causing its flight stability to be disrupted.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Drag increases disproportionately as pellet velocity increases, so it is generally better to increase pellet weight to keep velocities subsonic in high-powered guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Many shooters find that velocities in the 800–900 ft/s (240–270 m/s) range offer an ideal balance between power and accuracy.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Spring-piston guns, especially high-powered ("magnum") models, do still recoil as a result of the mainspring pushing the piston forward.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Although the recoil is less than that of some cartridge firearms, it can make the gun difficult to shoot accurately as the spring recoil is in effect while the pellet is still within the barrel.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Spring gun recoil also has a sharp forward component, caused by the piston hitting the front end of the pump chamber when the spring has fully decompressed.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] These rapid double-jerking movements are known to damage scopes not rated for spring gun usage.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] In addition, the spring often has unpredictable collateral transverse vibrations as well as torquing, both of which can cause accuracy to suffer.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The better quality spring guns can have very long service lives, being simple to maintain and repair.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Because they deliver the same mechanical energy output on each shot, external ballistics are quite consistent.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Most Olympic air gun competitions through the 1970s and into the 1980s were shot with spring-piston guns, often of the opposing-piston recoil-eliminating type.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Beginning in the 1980s, guns powered by compressed/liquefied carbon dioxide began to dominate the competition.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Today, the guns used at the highest levels of competition are powered by compressed air.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Some newer generation air guns incorporate a gas spring (commonly referred to as a *gas piston*, *gas ram*, *gas strut* or *nitro piston*) instead of a mechanical spring.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The spring itself is essentially a stand-alone enclosed piston pump without outlets and with pressurized air or inert gas (such as nitrogen) held tightly sealed within the cylinder.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] When the gun is cocked, the gas inside the cylinder gets further compressed by the piston, stores potential energy and acts as a pneumatic accumulator.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Gas spring units require higher precision to manufacture since they require a low-friction sliding seal that can withstand the high pressures within when cocked.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Gas springs perform more reliably in cold climates than coil springs, because metallic coil springs need to be coated with lubricating grease which often thickens in low temperatures causing the gun to "freeze up".
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Gas springs also have less lateral and longitudinal vibrations than coil springs, hence are usually less "hold-sensitive", making it easier to achieve consistent shot groupings.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Pneumatic airguns propel the projectiles by utilizing the pneumatic potential energy within compressed air, which is pressurized beforehand and stored inside the gun, and then released through valves during shooting.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Single-stroke and multi-stroke pump guns utilize an on-board hand pump to pressurize air in an internal reservoir tank, while pre-charged pneumatic guns' reservoirs are filled from an external source using either a high-pressure stand pump or by decanting air from a larger diving cylinder.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Because of the need for cylinders or charging systems, PCP guns have higher initial costs but much lower operating costs when compared to CO2 rifles, and have superior performance over ordinary pump guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Having no significant movement of heavy mechanical parts during the discharge cycle, PCP airgun designs produce lower recoil, and can shoot as many as 100 shots per charge depending on the tank/reservoir size.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The ready supply of air has allowed the development of semi- and fully automatic air guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] PCP guns are very popular in Europe because of their accuracy and ease of use.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] They are widely utilized in ISSF 10 meter air pistol and rifle shooting events and the sport of Field Target shooting, and are usually fitted with telescopic sights.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Early stand pump designs encountered problems of fatigue (both human and mechanical), temperature warping, and condensation – none of which are beneficial to accurate shooting or the airguns' longevity.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Modern stand pumps have multi-stage chambers and built-in air filtration systems and have overcome many of these problems.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Using scuba-quality air decanted from a diving cylinder provides consistently clean, dry, high-pressure air.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] During the typical PCP's discharge cycle, the hammer of the rifle is released by the sear to strike the bash valve.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The hammer may move rearwards or forwards, unlike firearms where the hammer almost always moves forward.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The valve is held closed by a spring and the pressure of the air in the reservoir.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The pressure of the spring is constant, and the pressure of the air released (which is also known as the *working pressure*) decreases with each successive shot.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] As a result, when the reservoir pressure is high, the valve opens less fully and closes faster than when the reservoir pressure is lower, resulting in a similar total volume of air flowing past the valve with each shot.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] This results in a degree of partial self-regulation that gives a greater consistency of velocity from shot to shot, which corresponds to the middle "plateau" phase of the gun's shot-to-shot muzzle velocity profile (also known as the *power curve* ).
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Well-designed PCP will display good shot-to-shot consistency over a long period, as the air reservoir is being depleted.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Other PCP rifles and pistols are regulated, i.e. the firing valve operates within a secondary chamber separated from the main air reservoir by the regulator body.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The regulator maintains the pressure within this secondary chamber at a set pressure (lower than the main reservoir's) until the main reservoir's pressure drops to the point where it can no longer do so.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] As a result, shot-to-shot consistency is maintained for longer than in an unregulated rifle, and the gun can also output more shots due to reduced waste of reservoir pressure.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] CO2 guns are popular for training, as the guns and ammunition are inexpensive, relatively safe to use, and no specialized facilities are needed for safety.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] In addition, they can be purchased and owned in areas where firearms possession is either strictly controlled or banned outright.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Most CO2 powered guns are relatively inexpensive, and there are a few precision target guns available that use CO2.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The high-pressure air (HPA) system, or *N2*, was originally developed for paintball markers as a replacement for CO2 cartridges, and uses powerlet interface-compatible diving cylinders filled with either pure nitrogen or compressed air (which is 78% nitrogen).
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Because nitrogen is more inert than CO2, it remains in the gaseous state longer when compressed; when it expands, it cools due to the Joule-Thomson effect, but at a far lower rate than liquid CO2 because there is no change in state from liquid to gas.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] This thermostability reduces the variation in output pressure associated with rapid successions of firing cycles, improving accuracy and reliability in extreme climates.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] However, because compressed air is stored at higher pressures (up to 34 MPa or 4,900 psi) than liquid CO2 (stored at around 8 MPa or 1,200 psi), HPA cylinders are more expensive.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Cylinders smaller than 1.1 L (67 cu in) may not even last as long as a standard CO2 cartridge when subjected to frequent use.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] It is also possible to power an HPA-compatible gun directly from a plug-in air compressor without using a gas cylinder, though this type of setup is rare.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Each air cartridge is essentially a self-contained gas reservoir housed inside a cartridge case (usually in the size of a .38 Special), with an internal bash valve designed to release the content when the base of the cartridge is struck.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Prior to shooting, each cartridge is pre-filled with sufficient compressed air for one shot (typically via a multi-stroke hand pump) and has a .177/.22 caliber pellet pre-seated to its front slot, and the entire cartridge is then inserted into a chamber in the gun barrel.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] When shooting, the hammer hits the rear of the air cartridge, mimicking the function of a centerfire ammunition.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] This allows the airgun to be constructed and operated in similar fashions to genuine firearms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] It also allows for higher shot consistency because each cartridge can be easily filled to an identical air charge, essentially removing the "power curve" of conventional PCP guns and bypassing any need for regulators.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] It also simplifies the magazine feed design and eliminates the risk of deforming the projectiles when the action seats each pellet, as the soft lead pellet is protected from contact with the action probe by the harder cartridge casing.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The air cartridge system, both in the rifle and revolver forms, was at the peak of its popularity throughout the 1990s.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The popularity of the Brocock range was such that, by 2002, estimates put the number of air cartridge guns in circulation around 70,000-80,000.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] However, a small number of incidents relating to the alleged illegal conversion of (mainly) Brococks to allow them to discharge live ammunition sparked a media frenzy.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] After the UK government implemented the Anti-social Behaviour Act 2003 in January 2004, it became illegal to possess such airguns without a firearm certificate in the United Kingdom.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Brocock subsequently ceased production of all air cartridge systems and turned to focus primarily on PCP airguns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The most popular ammunition used in rifled air guns is made of lead, a heavy metal.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Lead is highly poisonous (whether inhaled or swallowed), affecting almost every organ and system in the human body.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] For this reason, lead-free pellets are becoming increasingly popular, and are available in all major shapes and styles, just like traditional lead pellets.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] In flight, the skirt has greater drag-to-weight ratio than the head and exerts a rearward pull behind the center of mass, similar to that of a shuttlecock.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] This produces a phenomenon known as *drag stabilization*, which helps to counteract yawing and maintain a consistent flight path.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] However, the diabolo shape also means that the overall pellet will have poor ballistic coefficient and tends to lose energy quickly and be more unstable especially in the transonic region (272–408 m/s ~ 893–1340 ft/s).
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Diabolo pellets are conventionally made from lead, but are widely available in non-lead alternatives, such as tin, or a combination of materials such as steel or gold alloys with polymer tips.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] A variety of lead-free pellets are offered by all major pellet manufacturers, including H&N Sport, RWS, JSB, Gamo, and others.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Since lead is very dense, it has a higher ballistic coefficient than lightweight alternatives such as tin, copper, or plastic.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] At the present time, the airgun industry does not mass-produce dense alternatives to lead with a high ballistic coefficient for long-range shooting.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Some manufacturers also have recently introduced the more cylindro-conoidal-shaped "slug" pellets for the more powerful modern PCP air rifles.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Appropriately sized bullets cast from firearm bullet molds can be used in big bore air rifles.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Caution should be used when handling lead projectiles or preparing animals for food, as lead fragments can be easily missed inside the meat.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Lead-free slugs in airgun calibers are gradually being developed and becoming available for purchase from manufacturers such as Zan Projectiles, due in part to regulations on hunting with lead projectiles in many areas.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The BB shot was once the most common airgun ammunition in the US, thanks to the popularity of Daisy's line of BB airguns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] A BB is a small metallic ball in 4.5 mm/.177" diameter, typically made of steel (with a copper or zinc coating) or lead.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Originally called the "round shot", the contemporary name came from the "BB"- size lead birdshot used in shotgun shells, which the first BB gun invented in 1886 was designed to shoot.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Steel BBs can be acceptably accurate at short distances when fired from properly designed BB guns with smoothbore barrels.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Lead #3 buckshot pellets can be used in .25" caliber airguns as if they were large BBs.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Therefore, steel BBs lack the spin stabilization required for long-range accuracy, and usage in any but the cheapest rifled guns is discouraged.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The softer lead BBs, however, can be used in rifled barrels.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Typically BBs are used for indoor practice, casual outdoor plinking, training children, or to save money, as they are significantly cheaper than pellets.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Replica CO2 pistols allow people to train with a BB gun, saving a lot of money to centerfire firearm cartridges.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Care should be exercised to avoid ricochet, and safety glasses are recommended.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Recently, manufacturers have created frangible BBs, which break apart and do not ricochet, reducing the hazards associated with BB guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Some shotgunners use sightless BB rifles to train in instinctive shooting.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Similar guns were also used briefly by the United States Army in a Vietnam-era instinctive shooting program called "Quick Kill".
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] In the 18th and 19th centuries, air gun darts were popular, largely because they could be reused.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Although less popular now, several different types of darts are made to be used in air guns, but it is not recommended that darts be used in air guns with rifled bores or in spring-powered air guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Air guns that shoot darts are sometimes called *dart guns*, and *tranquilizer guns* if the darts used are loaded with anesthetic (tranquilizer) compounds.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Some modern air guns are designed to discharge arrows and are called *arrow guns* or sometimes *airbows*.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] These arrows are designed with a hollow shaft that is open in the rear where the nock would normally be.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] When loaded, the hollow arrow shaft is slid rearwards over a barrel whose external diameter is only fractionally smaller than the shaft's interior diameter, providing a close-enough fitting that minimizes rattling and gives a reasonable enveloping seal without causing too much friction.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] During shooting, the trigger releases high-pressure air from the barrel to the front portion of the hollow arrow shaft, pushing the arrow forward.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Such air guns can shoot arrows at launch velocities rivalling or even exceeding high-end crossbows, while retaining consistency of precision unaffected by archer's paradox, but they are also more expensive to set up and maintain.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The modern pentathlon has since 2009 included a laser-run event that replaced the traditional cross country run of 3,200 metres and timed air-pistol shoot.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The competitors run 4 laps of 800 m combined with 4 rounds of firing.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] The pistols used are modified air pistols that fire an eye-safe laser beam towards a target at the same time as a discharge of air.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] This has made the organisation of the events easier from a safety point of view and allows competitors to travel more easily with their weapons.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Airsoft pellets are plastic BBs shot from airsoft guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Larger caliber air rifles suitable for hunting large animals are offered by major manufacturers.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Custom air guns are available in even larger calibers such as 20 mm (0.79") or .87 (22.1 mm).
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] While in some countries air guns are not subject to any specific regulation, in most, there are laws which differ widely.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Each jurisdiction has its definition of an air gun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Regulations may vary for weapons of different bore, muzzle energy, velocity, or ammunition material.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Guns designed to fire metal pellets are often more tightly controlled than airsoft weapons.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] There may be a minimum age for possession, and sales of both air guns and ammunition may be restricted.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] Some areas require permits and background checks similar to those required for propellant type firearms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] While historical air guns have been made specifically for warfare, modern air guns can also be deadly.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] In medical literature, modern air guns have been noted as a cause of death.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] This has been the case for guns of caliber .177 and .22 that are within the legal muzzle energy of air guns in the United Kingdom.
[src:airsoft-pellets/air-gun] For reason of safety and security a rule of use of the safety flag has been strictly mentioned by ISSF for the 10m air pistol and rifle shooting sports events.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Depending on the mechanism for pellet propulsion, airsoft guns fall into two broad groups just like conventional airguns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] One group is spring-piston guns, which utilize elastic energy of a coil spring to propel piston air pump that is either manually cocked (i.e.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] "spring guns", commonly referred to as "*springers*", and are the simplest, cheapest and generally of low quality); or automatically cycled by a battery-powered electric motor gearbox (i.e.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] "gas guns"), which operate by bash valve-controlled pressure release of prefilled bottled gas such as compressed propane mixed with silicone oil (commonly known as "Green Gas") or CO2 canisters (Powerlets.).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Pneumatic guns can be cycled either manually by hand-pulling back the bolt or slide, which loads the subsequent shot; or automatically by having the released propellant gas also pushing back the action (i.e.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Airsoft guns are often designed to aesthetically resemble real firearms, which provides more realism but also makes it difficult to distinguish them from actual lethal weapons.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Airsoft in the past was used almost solely for recreational purposes, but in 2012, gas blowback (GBB) airsoft technology became adopted by US federal and state institutions as an affordable and reliable tactical training tool for close quarters battles.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] In 2018, the United States Coast Guard officially adopted SIG-branded P229 airsoft pistol for training.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Airsoft guns also allow basic and advanced shooter training in a safer environment by reducing the risks of accidental injury or death from a negligent discharge.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] There are clubs, teams, and even athletic associations devoted to airsoft events around the world.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Europe is home to some of the largest events, with skirmishes of over 2,000 people participating.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] In North America, in 2012 alone, Fulda Gap Airsoft Game in Taylorsville, North Carolina had over 1,100 participants, and Operation Lion Claws Military Simulation Series (OLCMSS) had 800 people attend at George Air Force Base in Victorville, California.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] American Mil-sim, Black Sheep, and Ballahack also host large games.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Events may include a variety of equipment ranging from small arms to armored vehicles.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] In many countries, every airsoft gun owner and active enthusiast must be affiliated with an accredited airsoft association or federation.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Most airsoft players host games at a registered field where combat situations are simulated using airsoft weaponry like replica pistols, submachine guns, carbines/assault rifles, DMRs/sniper rifles, light machine guns, grenades and landmines.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Great variety and profusion of militaria is usually used.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Historical reenactment of famous war situations is another favorite of many airsoft players and clubs.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] In addition, a number of companies such as Systema Engineering and Celsius Technology manufacture ultra-realistic high-velocity airsoft rifles designed specifically for the police and military for non-lethal training purposes.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] People today may also use airsoft guns as props for film making, particularly after the *Rust* shooting incident.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] An Airsoft Two-Tone Gun is an Airsoft replica which has been sprayed over 51% a bright, non military colour, so that it complies with the Violent Crimes Reduction Act (VCRA, 2006), allowing anyone to buy a replica without having to prove that they have a legitimate use for it.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Spring guns are generally inexpensive (except the high-power sniper rifles and shotguns), and may not last long (depending on the build quality) due to the tension exerted on the gun parts by the recoiling of a powerful spring.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] However, many spring guns can be modified and upgraded to last longer and shoot more powerfully.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Low-end spring guns tend to be much cheaper than their electric equivalents due to their lack of electrical components (electric motor/actuator, spring-gearbox assembly, battery and battery charger).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] These guns are less common in competitions because their rate-of-fire is a disadvantage against automatic guns in close combat, and they do not provide enough accuracy and power for long-range use.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] There are some exceptions, however, as higher-end spring-powered airsoft rifles can be quite expensive; these guns are typically suited for "marksman" applications in airsoft matches and provide competitive muzzle velocities.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Additionally, pump shotguns are sometimes used for both short and long range engagements.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] In colder weather, spring pistols are more reliable than gas-powered pistols and even the batteries on automatic electric pistols (AEPs) both of which can be adversely affected by extremely low temperatures.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] This represents one of the major advantages of spring airsoft gun, as it can be fired in practically any situation without relying on batteries or bottled gas.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] This independence from external power sources causes some players to favor spring-powered guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Spring guns are also less susceptible to the effects of water, where a battery-powered gun could short-circuit and malfunction when wet.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Because of their low price, availability, and simplicity, spring guns tend to act as training guns for new players.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] In the UK, they are affectionately known as "springers" and were often a player's introduction to the sport due to the entry-level cost in comparison to AEG and GBB weapons.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Some veteran airsoft players still rely on sniper rifle and shotgun-type spring guns as a primary weapon due to reliability, high power, accuracy, low noise, and ease of repair compared to AEGs and GBB guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Selective fire options among automatic, 3-round burst and semi-automatic operations are all possible, which gives these guns the popular name "**automatic electric guns**", or **AEGs**.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] They are the most commonly used and widely available type of airsoft gun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] AEGs were developed in Japan and the Japanese company Tokyo Marui is credited with creating the original gearbox system.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] In a Tokyo Marui AEG, the motor drives a train of three gears mounted inside a gearbox, which then loads a pump piston against a spring.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Once the spring is released, it pushes the piston plunger forward through the pump cylinder to propel a pellet resting within the chamber forward through the barrel and out of the muzzle.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Many manufacturers have now more or less replicated this basic model, adding reinforced parts or minor improvements.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The electric airsoft guns were powered primarily by nickel-metal hydride (NiMH) batteries with varying voltages and milliampere-hour ratings.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The most common battery is an 8.4 V large battery pack, with a capacity between 2200 and 5000 mAh.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Also available are "mini" and "stick" batteries, which generally have 900 ~ 1600 mAh capacities.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Voltages for NiMH batteries range from 7.2 V to 12 V.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The usual rule of thumb is that the higher the mAh rating, the longer the battery lasts; the higher the voltage, the higher the rate of fire.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The most common AEGs are the AR-15 series (such as M16 rifle and M4 carbine, sometimes referred to as the ArmaLite or Colt series), the H&K MP5 series, and the AK or Kalashnikov series.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Also increasingly popular is the H&K G36 and, more recently, the FN P90 and H&K MP7.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Subsequently, numerous parts for repairs and modifications are commonly available for these rifles.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Some airsoft guns are called *low-powered electric guns* (LPEGs) to distinguish them from the original, more expensive and more powerful AEGs even though their mechanical/electrical design and operation is similar.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] MPEGs are the middle ground between LPEGs and AEGs.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Some companies, like UTG with their popular MP5 and AK-47 models, have improved their quality to such an extent that some models are now considered more affordable AEGs.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Electric blowbacks, also known as EBBs, are typically available at lower prices than their battery-powered counterparts.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] They generally run on AAA or AA batteries.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Most models utilizing this system are rifles.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] EBBs simulate the blowback action of a real pistol or rifle.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Essentially an AEG in design, EBBs are just as powerful.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] However, a drawback to having the realistic recoil feature is the tendency of the battery to quickly deplete.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Additionally, blowbacks can cause extra stress on the gear box which may result in a shorter life span.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Automatic electric pistols, abbreviated AEPs, were first introduced by Tokyo Marui in 2005 with their Glock 18C (followed later by a Beretta 93R model).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] They were the first handguns to incorporate an electrically powered system that is capable of fully automatic operation.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] In cold weather, AEPs are often considered better sidearms than gas powered pistols, because batteries are not as badly affected by frigid weather.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Gases like CO2 and green gas are stored in liquid form and require heat in order to vaporize.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] A gas pistol at 10 °F (−12 °C) will usually only get one to two usable shots from a full magazine, and even will be at reduced power because of the lowered pressure of the gas.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Because the AEP gearbox and battery are smaller, the velocity of AEP BBs (usually between 200 and 280 ft/s (85.3 m/s)) is relatively slow by the standards of airsoft simulations, rendering them useful only for close-range simulation.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] However, the advanced hop up units on these new guns tend to compensate for the low power and can produce an effective range comparable to those of an AEG.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] CYMA has made a clone Glock 18C, which is a lower priced alternative.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] An AEP differs from electric blow-backs because the AEP has a fixed slide (in which there is no external movement of the slide during operation), while an EBB simulates the "blow back" action in the slide experienced in a real pistol or Gas Blow Back (GBB).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] An AEP, however, has much more power and accuracy.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] One of the newer AEP-styled guns is the Marui replica of the Heckler & Koch MP7.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] It is considerably larger than either of the other guns, and can be upgraded to a much higher power through the use of an external battery, but uses the same system as the AEP, so the classification is ambiguous.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] It is slightly more powerful than the others and is a suitable choice for CQB (Close Quarter Battle) games due to its small size and decent barrel- to gun-length ratio.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Some semi-automatic pistols can be modified to be automatic pistols.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] To make them more effective, they use rechargeable batteries supplied with the gun, which can be replaced with a larger battery to increase their ROF.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Due to restrictions on size, either the electric motor or batteries have to occupy space in the hand grip, reducing the available space for a magazine.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Because of this, most AEPs do not use a full size magazine found in most gas powered pistols.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] They are typically constructed almost entirely of plastic and have a light, toy-like feeling to them.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Gas-powered airsoft guns use the pneumatic potential energy stored within compressed gas to drive the shooting mechanism, and thus operate according to an entirely different design principle to spring- or electrically powered airsoft guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The most common type seen is the gas blowback (GBB) guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] These gas guns use an internal canister (usually within the magazine) that upon trigger-pull releases the prefilled bottled gas via a series of valves to propel the pellet and generate a blowback, which simulates recoil and cyclically loads the next shot.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] They are capable of both automatic and semi-automatic operation.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The most common gases used are "green gas" and propane which requires an adaptor.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] HFC-134a is also commonly used, particularly with pistols which have plastic sliders due to the lower pressure giving a smaller chance of damage to the weaker slide.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Less commonly used gases include "red gas" (which is actually HCFC-22), CO2 and nitrogen/high-pressure air.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] However, it is unlawful to use HCFC-22 as a propellant in the US, as it is a Class II ozone-depleting substance and its use as an aerosol propellant has been banned since January 1994 under section 610(d) of Clean Air Act.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Red gas is usually avoided unless the airsoft gun has undergone modification, as its relatively high critical pressure can cause damage to the airsoft gun, such as breakage of the slide or bolt.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] CO2, nitrogen, and high pressure air are less common because they need to be stored at higher pressures than "green gas" or HFC-134a.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The first ever gas powered airsoft guns were commonly referred to as "classic" guns, owing to their age.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] R-12 was a commonly used refrigerant for car air conditioning and refrigerators, and is considered a highly potent ozone-depleting substance and listed as a Class I Ozone Depleting Substance by the US EPA.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Its use as a general purpose aerosol propellant has been banned by the US EPA since March 1978 under 43 FR 11301 for use in aerosol use with a very few exceptions.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Its use is also banned in many countries under United Nations treaties.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] On December 31, 2008, the use of CFCs for medical inhalers was banned.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Later users modified these old guns to be powered by regulated CO2 canisters or nitrogen/high pressure air bottles to increase power and consistency.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] However, these guns have largely been superseded by the newer and more versatile AEGs, or automatic electric guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] One of the reasons for this is because the most commonly available propellant, R-12, is costly.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Additionally, at high flow rates, liquid propellants tend to cool down, eventually freezing.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] As cooldown progresses, the rate of fire gradually decreases until the gun ceases operation.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The user would then be forced to wait for the propellant to warm up again.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] CO2 is not affected as badly by this tendency, and nitrogen/high pressure air is immune to it.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Furthermore, if liquid propellant is introduced into the gun's mechanism, rubber parts can freeze and eventually damage the gun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] However, it is unlikely for this to occur since once the gas is released from the containing cylinder it instantly turns back into its gaseous state, and expands rapidly.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] It is doubtful whether the retained pressure behind the BB before it begins to accelerate down the barrel is enough to keep the gas in a liquid form.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Also, any gun that is expected to be exposed to the intense cold of de-pressurizing gas should have materials that can handle it.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Gas power tends to be used in airsoft pistols where size constraints make electric-powered mechanisms impractical.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Other instances where gas is favored are where adjustable velocities are required or where a blowback feature is desired.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] A blowback feature is a mechanism which cycles a slide or bolt to better simulate a real firearm's operation.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Because of the mechanical complexities involved with distributing and regulating gas, these guns have largely given way to electric guns for less specialized applications, however, they still remain favorable amongst most airsofters.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] They are not just limited to pistols; submachine guns, sniper rifles and assault rifles commonly use gas mechanisms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Whilst the submachine gun replicas typically feature a blowback mechanism similar to the pistol replicas, sniper rifle replicas usually omit the blowback mechanism in favor of reduced recoil and increased muzzle velocity.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Along with using gas to power guns, it is also applied for use in replica grenades.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] These grenades are either projectiles, fired from a grenade launcher such as the M203 or GP-25, or throwable.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The shells work on the system of an internal piston, filled with gas.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Either a series of BB's or in some cases a rubber or soft foam head is seated in or on top of the shell.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] When the pressure is released the projectile(s) are shot from the launcher sent downrange.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] In the case of the throwable grenades, inside the grenade there is a similar piston to the one used in the shells, but is on a literal "timer" that allows the user to clear the area of effect.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] BBs or powder acts as the projectile in the case of these grenades.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Currently both types of grenades are not very common, mostly because grenade launchers are quite expensive and the throwable grenades are not very reliable.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] High pressure air (HPA) systems are a type of pneumatic airsoft weapon that use externally supplied high pressure air instead of internal gas canisters like the majority of gas-operated airsoft guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] They work by using a separate high-pressure air tank that is connected to the airsoft gun with a hose, which is connected with a pneumatic motor inside the gun (called an "engine") at where the gearbox would be in a normal electric airsoft gun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The engine is powered by a fire control unit that can adjust to the desired rates of fire as well as the dwell that determines how much air is released with each individual shot.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Airsoft gun manufacturer Systema Engineering (PTW) developed a line of airsoft guns and accessories intended for military and law enforcement training.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] These airsoft guns are made of aircraft-grade aluminium combined with stainless steel parts that gives strength, stability, weather protection, and easy maintenance.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] These training weapons offer a more realistic display of military weapons.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Unfortunately they have been plagued by reliability problems and parts availability.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] They have also had models banned from the US for being capable of being converted into real firearms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Two manufactures, King Arms and KWA, came out with ATF-approved gas blowback AR-15 replicas that allowed for correct weapons tear down, manipulation and function that were designed for military use, but were also legal for US citizens to own.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The King Arms model required upgrade parts out of the parts to give it reliability, though the KWA was plagued by a weak hop-up system, but otherwise reliable.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Airsoft guns shoot plastic pellets at velocities from 30 m/s (98 ft/s) for a low-end spring pistol, to 200 m/s (660 ft/s) for heavily upgraded customized sniper rifles.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Most non-upgraded AEGs are in the middle, producing velocities from 90 m/s (300 ft/s) to 120 m/s (390 ft/s).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The internal components of most guns can be upgraded which can increase the pellet velocity significantly.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Using heavier pellets (.25 g, .3 g, etc.) will significantly reduce the gun's muzzle velocity, but can increase accuracy at range and reduce susceptibility to wind drift.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Lighter pellets have less kinetic energy than their heavier pellets, despite their higher exit velocity.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Decreasing the pellet's weight does not generally increase its range.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] A common upgrade done by players is in the "hop-up" system, featured in most mid- to high-end AEGs, as well as gas guns and spring sniper rifles.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] In this system, the wall of a rubber tube, called a bucking, is forced into the upper path of the pellet right before it begins flying down the inner barrel.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] This contact imparts backspin, which in turn gives the pellet a Magnus lift to maintain a flatter trajectory for a longer period of time.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] This is adjusted by screws or gears that cause the bucking to only show a small or large presence in the barrel.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Different degrees of firmness of the rubber are considered when a hop-up is being upgraded.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Airsoft is safe when played with proper protective gear.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Most airsoft guns on the market are usually below 350 ft/s (110 m/s), but projectiles expelled from any type of airsoft gun can travel as slow as 65 ft/s (20 m/s) to more than 700 ft/s (210 m/s) and are capable of breaking skin at 350–400 ft/s (110–120 m/s).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] For example, skirmish play in the United Kingdom has a maximum of 350 ft/s, with some airsoft locations having a limit as low as 290 ft/s.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] If under 300 ft/s (91 m/s), the hit would have to be within a short range.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Blood can be drawn, but injuries that do occur are predominantly superficial.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Full-seal protective eyewear (goggles or glasses) is widely considered the minimum protection for airsoft players, as the eyes may be injured by any type of impact.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The least amount of protection a player should seek will meet or exceed ANSI/ISEA Z87.1 standards, which indicates the eyewear is rated for ballistic strikes.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Mesh eyewear has also seen some limited use by players due to low cost and its inability to fog, although it has drawn some criticism for its non-impact rated construction and vulnerability to debris.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Some impacts (particularly at close range with powerful guns) are capable of cracking or damaging teeth.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Dentists have reported broken teeth that require root canal and crowns to repair damage.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] A face mask (like that used for paintball) is recommended to protect eyes and teeth.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Metallic mesh masks and mouth guards have recently seen popular use.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] There are legal issues in airsoft as well as several rules imposed in a game by game basis.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Most indoor airsoft fields only allow up to 350 ft/s (110 m/s), and most outdoor fields begin capping near the 410 ft/s (125 m/s) for rifles and 525 ft/s (160 m/s) for long-range guns such as sniper rifles.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Most outdoor fields also impose a minimum engagement distance for guns firing over a certain range, normally for squad support weapons and sniper rifles.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] In order for an airsoft gun to cause any serious injury, it would have to be well over these limits and in close proximity.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] To even reach such speeds, the gun would have to be highly modified.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] So it is therefore unlikely to cause permanent or serious damage with any stock airsoft gun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The use of metallic BBs, or any foreign objects, is very dangerous for the user and other people and property in close vicinity, and may damage the airsoft gun as well.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] However, specially designed and built metallic 6 mm BBs for airsoft guns can be found on the market.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] These metallic BBs should not be used for airsoft play because they can break through goggles and other safety gear.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Plastic BBs can be a mixture of PLA and Plastic causing less damage to persons.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Although airsoft guns in the United States are generally sold with a 6 mm (0.24in.) or longer orange tip on the barrel in order to distinguish them from real firearms, this is not in fact required by federal law.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Full or partial preventive painting of airsoft guns as a legal obligation to avoid confusion of the airsoft replicas with real lethal weapons is in practice in several jurisdictions around the world.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] A common controversy referred to as "pumping" or "roping" is the act of purposely firing 20+ airsoft rounds at one player until they run away or submit in pain.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Popular videos such as *Rip Kid* and *SC Trip 2015* have both documented the act of pumping.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] A CBS News report noted that since from 2014 to 2024, more than 300 people had been shot and killed by police while holding realistic replica guns, of which 19 were minors.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Some airsoft guns can be such accurate replicas that they violate intellectual property laws (specifically those regarding trademarks), most notably some models from Tokyo Marui bearing Colt or Heckler & Koch trademarks that may not be imported into the United States.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Certain companies such as Classic Army or ICS avoid this problem by licensing their replicas from the original manufacturers, such as ArmaLite by license from ActionSportGames or Olympic Arms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] The airsoft company ActionSportGames has licensed trademark rights from many well-known firearm manufacturers, such as Armalite, Dan Wesson, CZ, Steyr, STI, B&T and Franchi.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Another company who licence the designs of gun companies is Evolution International.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] It has a portfolio of exclusive licenses from ADC Armi Dallera Custom, TangoDown, Z-M Weapons, DSR precision, Lone Star Tactical, and SAR.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] In addition, there have been reports of companies taking action in defense of their intellectual property rights.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Some end users have made attempts to sell their guns, some in the style of Glock pistols, only to find Glock blocking the sale and threatening legal action.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] In addition to these actions, Glock, as well as Heckler & Koch, have blocked the sale, trade and distribution of replicas bearing resemblance to their products.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] Recently, Glock gave the licensing to the Glock name and likeness to Elite Force/Umarex to produce replica models of the real Glock series of firearms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] In response, SIG Air, SIG Sauer's airgun division, announced on January 17, 2019, that it was introducing its own in-house ProForce airsoft line for professional training, with the initial offerings include the M17 and P229 airsoft pistol.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-gun] SIG Air also announced that "we are rapidly expanding the SIG AIR business, and it is important to us to assume full control to ensure all SIG Air products are of the highest quality", and it would no longer be licensing the "SIG" brand or trademarks for sale by commercial airsoft manufacturers.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Although the majority of pellets bought and used are simple spherical projectiles made of plastic, some of the following special varieties can be used to give a player an advantage, such as higher quality pellets.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Biodegradable pellets are available, and are often required by outdoor fields where sweeping is not an option.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Conventional pellets pollute the environment, as most non-biodegradable pellets have a mineral or petroleum-based center, coated in non-biodegradable plastics, thus ensuring they will stay in the environment for several hundred years if not collected.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Biodegradable pellets are made of various types of resin, often developed for the agricultural industry, and better makes are certified as compostable.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Commonly used plastic resins include polylactic acid or polylactide (PLA) which is based on renewable materials like corn products and a molecular formula of (C3H4O2)n.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] There is a mixture of degradable processes being used, such as soil microbes and photosensitive degradation.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Biodegradable pellets are currently being produced with all the characteristics of the best of the conventional, with homogeneous resin construction.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Most high-quality pellets are available in a non-biodegradable version, as well as a biodegradable version that costs slightly more.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Both bio- and non-biodegradable pellets are popular and widely available.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Glow-in-the-dark pellets, known as *tracer* pellets, can be used in conjunction with a device that "charges" the pellets by flashing them with a burst of light before leaving the barrel so that they remain luminescent in flight for use during nocturnal games/operations.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] This tracer unit is usually hidden from view, often disguised as a suppressor, or is included inside the magazine or hop-up unit.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] There are also biodegradable tracer pellets available.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] This type of pellet is dark-colored so that the opponent has a tougher time spotting the pellets' origin, as the most common pellet color is white, which makes it easy for the opposition to spot the shooter by following the trail of pellets.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Two major problems of this variant of pellet are that there are few high-quality pellets in this color and the shooter has a difficult time seeing their own trail of shots.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Paint-filled pellets are also available, called "paintballs", which are very similar to those used in paintball.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Airsoft models equipped with the hop-up projectile stabilizing system are not able to use these, as the thin shells are liable to break in the barrel, covering the inside with paint.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] These special pellets are also incompatible with airsoft models using mechanized feeding systems, such as high capacity magazines, for the same reason.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] With some companies, the use of paintballs voids the airsoft gun's warranty; paint may get into the mechanical workings of the airsoft gun and damage parts beyond simple maintenance.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] These issues may be fixed by removing the hop-up unit, which can void the warranty, and also switching to a low or mid-capacity magazine with no mechanized feed.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] A specialized pellet coated in a powder or liquid that leaves a small colored mark when it strikes a surface.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] The powder deposits from these pellets are left in any part of the airsoft gun or storage unit that the pellet comes in contact with; build-up over time, without cleaning, can cause malfunctions or damage to moving parts.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Made from (most commonly) 100% silica, the material in these pellets is very evenly distributed, improving flight characteristics.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Some accounts indicate that these pellets are capable of breaking glass and industry-standard protective eyewears.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Due to safety concerns and reports of injuries caused by this type of pellets, it is commonly prohibited in professional airsoft facilities.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Metal pellets are also marketed for use in airsoft guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] These pellets are heavier and harder than conventional polymer pellets, and the impact from a metal pellet can injure players.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Safety concerns make metallic pellets suitable only for target shooting.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] The added weight reduces the effect of crosswind on the pellet, imparting more accuracy when fired at longer ranges in outdoor environments where wind would significantly alter the trajectory of traditional pellets.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Many airsoft locations where players can pay to play against others prohibit the use of metallic pellets due to the fact they are more likely to penetrate skin.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Metallic pellets are mostly used in a standard pump-action or carbon dioxide-powered BB guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Created from laboratory-grown crystal lattice structures, these pellets are individually machined to precise specifications that ensure uniform weight, dimensions and surface shape.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] This precision and uniformity provides ideal ballistic performance and consistent flight patterns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] The manufacturing process and materials are much more costly than molded polymer pellets – as a result, ceramic pellets are considerably more expensive than standard airsoft pellets.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Translucent pellets come in many colors.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] They tend to be non-biodegradeable and it can be difficult to find high quality versions compared to their opaque counterparts.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Pellet mass is an important factor when choosing pellets.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] A player's choice of pellet mass is governed by their gaming style (assaulting vs. sniping), the airsoft gun used (internal parts), game venue condition (in/outdoor) and size, and muzzle velocity regulations.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Also, the quality of the individual pellets may influence choice of price-range or manufacturer.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Low-cost pellets are often considered to have such negative characteristics as residual plastic from the moulding process (flash); lower impact resistance and some deviation from perfect spherical shape.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Cheaper pellets are known to shatter when fired, which can cause irreparable damage to the internals of the gun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Higher cost BBs generally have a smoother finish, are more impact resistant and are perfectly spherical.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] 6 mm is the industrial standard size used in almost all spring, electric and gas airsoft guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] A wide variety of pellet masses are also available for different usages.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] 8 mm (0.315 in) pellets are most commonly used in gas-powered airsoft shotguns with high velocities.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] The pellet speed of spring-powered and automatic electric guns is determined in large part by the tension of the gun's main spring.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Muzzle velocity limits are between 90 and 120 m/s (300 and 390 ft/s) for AEGs and 120 to 170 m/s (390–560 ft/s) for single-shot spring sniper rifles.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] For comparison purposes, 3.00 g (46+3⁄10 gr) is the typical mass of a paintball pellet, and 0.2 g (3+9⁄100 gr) is the standard for an airsoft pellet.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] At 3 g mass, a pellet flying at 100 m/s (330 ft/s) has 15 J of kinetic energy, while a 0.20 g has 1 J.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] It is important to distinguish that, in airsoft, the terminal impact energy is very close to the kinetic energy of the pellet because the collision is almost completely elastic.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] On the other hand, in paintball, the pellet fractures upon impact, leading to an inelastic collision with energy loss, and thus the impact energy is smaller than the kinetic energy of the pellet.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Nevertheless, the typical impact energies of the airsoft pellet tend to be much smaller than of the paintball.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] While a pellet's muzzle velocity is important for safety proposes, it will lose velocity during flight due to drag.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] where *v* is the instantaneous velocity of the pellet.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] For typical values of the pellet (*m* = 0.2 g, *v* = 120 m/s, *D* = 6 mm), the drag can be very high ( $576\ \mathrm {m} /\mathrm {s} ^{2}$ ), which means that the velocity decreases quite fast.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] In particular, for typical values and neglecting wind effects or hop-up usage, a straight shot from a height of 1.8 m (5.9 ft) has a range of 34 m (37 yd).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] On ground hit, the impact energy of the pellet is 0.1 J.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] However, the same shot at close quarters (e.g.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] 5 m distance) has an impact energy of 1 J (see figure).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Airsoft pellets travelling with sufficient velocity can leave small superficial wounds when hitting exposed skin.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] While this can be painful, these wounds are typically closed contusions and heal quickly without needing any medical attention.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] However, pellets can cause more serious damage to the more vulnerable parts of the body, such as the eyes and ears.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Lower protective face masks are recommended during airsoft matches to shield players' nose, mouth, teeth and ears, and goggles or other protective eyewear are mandatory for eye protection.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] where *m* is the mass of a spherical bullet, in grams.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Penetration is defined here as entering the skin to a depth of more than half of the spherical pellet's diameter.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Accordingly, a typical 0.20 g airsoft pellet will penetrate the skin at 136.7 m/s (448 ft/s).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Because many high-end AEGs, spring- and gas-powered airsoft guns can achieve such velocity at close ranges, many airsoft venues set strict limits on the maximum muzzle velocities allowed on the field, requiring each player to undergo a chronograph test prior to participating in a game.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft-pellets] Some venues even have restrictions on minimal engagement distances, where shooting at opponents nearer than a set distance is prohibited, and a "bang bang" rule (players imitate firing by shouting "bang bang" instead of really firing the weapon) is often implemented.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Although similar to paintball in concept and gameplay, airsoft pellets do not leave visible dye markings on their target and hits are not always apparent, though the pellets can sometimes leave small bruises or welts on exposed skin (and so protective gear is still recommended).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The game therefore relies heavily on an honor system in which players who have been hit are expected to call themselves out of play in keeping with honesty, fairness and sportsmanship.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The airsoft guns used are mostly magazine-fed, with some having manual/battery motor-powered spring-piston pump power plants similar to Nerf Blasters, or pneumatically powered by replaceable compressed gas (e.g. propane ("green gas"), 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane or CO2) canisters.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Many airsoft guns also have mounting platforms compatible with genuine firearm accessories, and most cosmetically resemble real firearms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] This makes them popular for military simulation and historical reenactments.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] There are also professional gun safety and weapon manipulation training conducted with airsoft in some fields, such as law enforcement training, due to better safety and lower cost.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The United States Coast Guard, for instance, officially adopted airsoft for training in 2018.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Airsoft gameplay varies in style and composition, but often ranges from action shooting to short organized live action role-playing (LARP) scenarios, close quarters battle skirmishes, military simulations (MilSim) or historical reenactments.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] It is played in indoor courses or outdoor fields.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Combat situations on the field may involve the use of genuine military tactics to achieve objectives set in each game.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Participants may attempt to emulate the tactical equipment and accessories used by modern military and police organizations.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] A game is normally kept safe by trained professionals acting as supervisors and marshals.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Before gameplay, an airsoft gun's muzzle velocity is usually checked through a chronograph and usually measured in feet per second (FPS) or joules, a measurement for kinetic energy.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Some countries have a set velocity or muzzle energy restriction; guns shooting over the legal muzzle velocity can be confiscated.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Some playing fields further restrict minimum engagement distances, requiring players to yell "Bang Bang!" or other verbal phrases in order to prevent shooting other players at close distances, which may cause injury.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] In certain countries use of laser sights of any kind is illegal, including gun scopes with integrated lasers.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Airsoft originated in postwar Japan during the early 1970s, when photographer Ichiro Nagata, an avid shooting enthusiast himself, thought about making modelguns that shoot real projectiles that could not kill or wound.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Early airsoft guns use a manual spring-piston design and are essentially single-shot, tailoring to the needs of shooting enthusiasts while conforming to Japan's strict weapons control laws.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Originally designed for target shooting, the plastic balls used in these "guns" can be shot at humans without causing injury due to the low muzzle energy.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] These new-generation replica guns were trademarked as **soft air guns** because the refrigerant propellant used was significantly weaker ("soft") than the canistered CO2 used in proper airguns (pellet guns and BB guns).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] This practical convenience of AEGs led soft air guns to quickly become popular for casual MilSim games, which the Japanese call **survival games** (サバイバルゲーム, *sabaibaru gēmu*).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Asahi Firearms was also a model company from Japan who operated in the 1980s and 90s and was one of the early pioneers of the airsoft hobby.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Airsoft guns spread to the United Kingdom in the late 1980s and early 1990s via a company called LS.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] They were sold in separate pieces and had to be assembled out-of-box before they were capable of shooting.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] These then became available to the rest of Europe and North America and rapidly gained popularity worldwide.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Since the mid-1980s, airsoft has been adapted with a purely recreational application in mind, and the sport is enjoyed by all ages.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Airsoft replicas are produced globally, with the majority being manufactured in East Asia.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Many law enforcement agencies and military units within the United States now start using airsoft for force-on-force tactical training drills.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The guns used in airsoft are typically classified as imitation firearms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] They have a mechanism for shooting projectiles 6 mm, 6.4 mm, or 8 mm in diameter.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Some companies produce full replicas of counterpart grenade launchers which fire a projectile spray of 6 millimetres (0.24 in) pellets by use of a high-powered spring mechanism or a compressed gas propellant (i.e. green gas, propane, compressed air, or CO2).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] There is also a type of airsoft gun that is powered by a single (HPA) high-pressure air tank and a battery pack to power the internal FCU "Fire Control Unit" computer board.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] These guns are often known for their high and adjustable RPS or "Rounds Per Second" and durability.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] These HPA replicas are most often referred to as "PolarStars", although this refers to a popular brand of HPA engines and accessories.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] A typical airsoft gun is noticeably lighter than its "real steel" counterpart due to the use of aluminum alloy and plastic materials, though some have added weights in them for a more realistic feel.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Japan has specific rules about producing airsoft guns with metal parts, while newer guns, especially those made in Taiwan and Mainland China, have both internal and external parts that are metallic.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Smoke caps, as well as noise amplifiers, are available for certain airsoft guns to add realism.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Gas handgun magazines usually contain 10 to 30 pellets in a standard-capacity magazine; however, some are high-capacity magazines and can hold 50 rounds or more.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] In the case of AEG rifles, magazines come in either real-capacity (equivalent to the 30-round capacity of its real steel counterpart), low-capacity (10–50 rounds), mid-capacity (75–250 rounds), or high-capacity (250+ rounds).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] These magazines have spring followers like in BB guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The high-cap magazines often have a ratchet wheel that can be wound up periodically to force pellets up from the holding chamber of the magazine to the feeding chute.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Due to loose pellets in the reservoir, they often make a rattling noise when running or walking.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Some airsoft guns have a battery-powered box or drum magazine that holds thousands of pellets, but these are usually only used and allowed on LMGs (light machine gun) type replicas.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] It is common for owners to "tech" (modify) their guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The majority of gearboxes are made to Tokyo Marui specifications and have aftermarket upgrade parts available commercially.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Some gearboxes are proprietary in design.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] It is also possible to perform DIY modifications.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The "hop-up" system, which is installed in most stock airsoft rifles and pistols, is used to increase effective ranges by putting backspin on the pellets.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The Magnus effect causes the pellets to experience more lift as they are shot, counteracting against gravity.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] A small rubber nub protrudes into the top of the barrel through a small hole, applies pressure on a rubber bucking, and catches the top of the pellet as it moves past.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Adjusting the hop-up makes the nub more or less protrude into the bucking, so that backspin is increased or reduced.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Ideally, the hop-up should be adjusted so that the pellets fly as far as possible in a straight line without curving upward too far or dropping too quickly.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Hop-Up does decrease the muzzle velocity (a gun firing 340 ft/s (100 m/s) with the hop fully unwound can drop to as low as 300 ft/s (91 m/s)).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Ease and location of adjustment vary by gun design; some equipment provides a control that can be adjusted quickly during gameplay, while others may require partial disassembly.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] For example, a common location for Hop-Up adjustment is where the ejection port would be on a real firearm, which allows the machine to be covered while still allowing quick access to adjust the Hop-Up.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Some players customize their airsoft guns, either to improve performance or for purely aesthetic reasons.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Additions include scopes, fore-grips, and flashlights, red dot sights being the most commonly used.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Red dot sights are used to help aim, fore-grips are used to get a better grip on the airsoft gun, and flashlights (whether mounted or held in another hand) are used to illuminate dark areas and/or to blind opponents.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Even though in certain countries lasers are illegal, they are popular attachments in the U.S. and Europe.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Also available are "mock suppressors/silencers".
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] These resemble the actual firearm accessory that dampens sound.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Since Airsoft does not use combustibles for propulsion these usually serve no function.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Although there are models that function to "light up" a glow-in-the-dark BB using UV light similar to a tracer round.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Most airsoft guns fire round plastic pellets, usually white, but Tracers are common as well.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The pellets mostly range from 0.12 to 0.48 g.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] However, the most popular weights for AEGs (automatic electric guns) and GBB* (Gas Blow-Back guns) are 0.20 g to 0.32 g (whose muzzle velocity ranges from approximately 250 ft/s (76 m/s) to 400 ft/s (120 m/s)).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Heavier rounds (0.36–0.40 g) are typically used in long-range and sniper applications since they are more stable in flight and less easily deflected by wind.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The pellets, which are called BBs (ball bearings), are usually bought in bags or bottles of 2,000 to 5,000, but other sizes are available, such as a 250,000 round (65 kg) package of tournament grade BBs.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Biodegradable BBs are a fraction more expensive than non-bio counterparts, but many fields require them.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] BBs are typically 5.95mm ±0.01 mm in diameter.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Due to the low muzzle energy (less than 1.5 J or 1.1 ft⋅lb even for high-power models) and poor sectional density, the pain an airsoft pellet causes on skin impact is about the same as getting pinched.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] As a reference value, a standard 0.20 gram 6 mm pellet, which is the most common size and weight, traveling at 100 m/s (330 ft/s) has 1 J (0.74 ft⋅lb) of kinetic energy.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Calculating the kinetic energy of an airsoft projectile is important for ensuring player safety.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] While a projectile’s ability to cause injury or penetrate a surface technically depends on energy density—that is, the kinetic energy divided by the impact area—this variable is nearly constant in airsoft, as most BBs have standardized diameters of 6 mm or 8 mm.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] As a result, the primary factor affecting the potential for injury or penetration is simply the kinetic energy of the BB.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Despite this, safety limits in airsoft are often expressed solely in FPS, which fails to account for variations in BB mass.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] where m is the mass in kilograms and v is the speed in meters per second.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Different regions vary in the velocity airsoft guns are allowed to shoot at.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] In the United States, velocity differs from the type of gameplay field.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Close Quarter Battle arenas typically regulate velocity on airsoft guns at around 110 m/s (350 ft/s).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] For outdoor fields, velocity is usually regulated by the type of gun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] With a standard 0.20 grams (3.1 gr) pellet, fully automatic Airsoft Electric Guns (AEGs) are often set at less than 120 m/s (400 ft/s), semi-automatic DMR-style AEGs at 120–140 m/s (400–450 ft/s), and bolt-action (manually cocked spring-piston) sniper rifles at 140–150 m/s (450–500 ft/s).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The maximum effective range of field-legal airsoft guns is around 100 m (110 yd) with a highly upgraded sniper rifle replica.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Most airsoft guns used for field play will have an effective range of around 43–67 m (47–73 yd), depending on the intended gameplay role.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Most Airsoft guns are capable of shooting from 60 to 125 m/s (200 to 410 ft/s), although it is also possible to purchase upgraded internals that will enable the gun to shoot up to 170 m/s (550 ft/s) or higher.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] In California, a common limit for CQB is 110 m/s (350 ft/s).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] In Ireland, Italy and Japan the muzzle energy limit for airsoft guns is 1 joule no matter what the type of gameplay.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] In the UK, the law allows weapons locked to semi-automatic and bolt-action rifles to fire up to 2.5 joules (at muzzle velocity up to 158 m/s or 518 ft/s).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Any weapon "which is capable of discharging two or more missiles successively without repeated pressure on the trigger" is limited, by law, at 1.3 joules (velocity up to 114 m/s or 374 ft/s).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Northern Ireland has a maximum velocity of 100 m/s (330 ft/s) with 0.20 g pellets, without regard to the type of equipment.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] In Sweden, the legal limitations of airsoft guns caps the energy limit at 10 joules for manual guns, and 3 joules for semi- and fully automatic guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The ballistics of spring- or electrically powered airsoft guns differ from real firearms in that a longer barrel will not always result in better accuracy.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The "sweet spot" for barrel length in a spring/electric powered airsoft gun is around 450 mm (18 in), beyond which added barrel length will not improve accuracy.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] In any case, barrel quality, velocity consistency, and hopup quality/design are more important factors with regard to accuracy.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Added barrel length will result in slightly increased velocity if the cylinder size and compression are appropriate for the barrel length.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] For example, a gun with a large cylinder and a long barrel will shoot slightly harder than a gun with a small cylinder and a short barrel (*ceteris paribus*).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] This rule will apply even for barrels longer than 500 mm (20 in), if there is enough cylinder volume and air compression to propel the pellet through the barrel.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] However, the resulting velocity increase will be hardly noticeable.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The only considerable advantage of using a longer inner barrel in an AEG or spring-powered gun is that it generally will make the gun quieter due to the weakened muzzle pop.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] In gas-powered guns, added barrel length (to an appropriate extent) can result in increased velocity and accuracy to a degree.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Tighter-bore barrels will increase velocity because there will be less space between the pellet and the barrel for the air to escape through.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Most stock airsoft guns have 6.03–6.05 mm (0.237–0.238 in) bore barrels, but best performance is usually seen with "tightbore" barrels, which are 6.01–6.05 mm (0.237–0.238 in) in diameter.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] However, the tighter the bore, the more likely the chance of a pellet jam, and subsequently, tightbores need to be cleaned and lubricated regularly.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] It is generally agreed upon that a high-quality 6.01-6.02 mm barrel will provide the highest muzzle velocity, while a good-quality 6.03 mm or 6.05 mm barrel will provide the best compromise between power, accuracy and ease of maintenance.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The actual accuracy difference between tightbore sizes is debatable and usually outweighed by bore consistency.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Although, with the newfound popularity with HPA guns, the debate has been opened that barrels with a larger diameter (up to 6.13 mm or 0.241 in) could provide a more accurate shot.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Due to the higher volume of air surrounding the pellet it negates the chance of the pellet coming into contact with the barrel, throwing the pellet's trajectory off, similar to a musket, in how the bullet slams about before leaving the barrel.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Airsoft guns are not to be confused with BB guns, which are airguns that shoot 4.5 mm (.177 in) metallic spherical pellets, unlike the plastic pellets shot by airsoft guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Many manufacturers and retailers suggest treating an airsoft gun like a real gun at all times.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] This will help alleviate safety issues resulting in an accidental/negligent discharge, or prevent a public panic due to a carelessly displayed airsoft gun being mistaken for a real firearm.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Most manufacturers include an orange tip on the muzzle of the airsoft gun for signaling and safety purposes, and most retailers urge consumers not to remove the orange tip as it is used to help distinguish them from a real firearm.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The orange tip serves many purposes, one of them being for law enforcement to help discern airsoft guns from real firearms and thus prevent unnecessary excessive forces.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The minimum safe level of gear required to participate in most games includes a pair of ANSI Z87.1 eye protection, preferably a fully sealed APEL-rated ballistic eyewear.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Traditional prescription glasses and sunglasses, or goggles not rated sufficiently for impact-resistance, may shatter and/or be perforated upon being struck when used for airsoft or paintball, causing injury to the eye.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Masks, face shields and other types of full-face coverings such as balaclavas are recommended at most airsoft fields.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Rules such as a maximum muzzle velocity and engagement distance guidelines are used by different groups.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Some organizations have created common safety rules and guidelines.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Most minimum engagement distances are 10 feet (3.0 m).
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] When not actively playing, some fields require "barrel bags", also known as barrel socks, barrel condoms, barrel blockers, or barrel sleeves, to be placed over the muzzle of the gun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The magazine is usually removed as well, and the gun fired to clear the chamber.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Most fields also require players to leave their guns set to the safety position when they are not shooting, a practice common when using real firearms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] In certain countries, such as the Philippines, additional special rules have been adopted.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Airsoft is legal in most parts of the world.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Some countries have specific restrictions, such as maximum muzzle velocity and "unrealistic" coloring to distinguish them from actual firearms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] They are legal throughout the United States, but restrictions do exist in cities like Chicago and Detroit.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The states of New Mexico, New York and New Jersey, however, do not allow airsoft guns to be used or handled publicly because of the resemblance to real firearms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] They may be used on private property with the consent of the owner.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Customs and Border Protection FAQ page states that Airsoft guns are considered look-alike firearms which require the special blaze orange marking.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] In Ireland, Airsoft guns are classified as Realistic Imitation Firearms but not restricted as much as in the United Kingdom.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Under the Criminal Justice Act of 2006, Airsoft guns are legal in the Republic.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] One can buy, sell and import Airsoft guns without notifying relevant law enforcement authorities.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] They do not need to be painted in fluorescent colours, they do not need to have an orange tip, but they cannot launch the projectile with a kinetic energy exceeding 1 joule.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] However, carrying an imitation firearm in public is prohibited, and a gun carry case is required, as for real firearms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Airsoft shops are spread over the country, and buyers must be aged 18 or over to purchase an airsoft gun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] There is no age limit on Airsoft, as long as a minor has an adult's permission.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] In the United Kingdom, most Airsoft guns are classified as realistic imitation firearms or RIFs.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The sale, manufacture, or importation (but not gifting) of these is illegal under the Violent Crime Reduction Act 2006.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] A defence is allowed for selling for specific purposes including airsoft skirmishing.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The minimum age for buying any imitation firearm in the UK is 18.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] It is an offence to possess an imitation firearm in a public place without a reasonable excuse, for example traveling to, or from, or being at an airsoft skirmish site.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Most UK airsoft sites and retailers participate in the United Kingdom Airsoft Retailer Association Ltd (UKARA) registration scheme.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] A player who has participated in at least 3 skirmishes over a period of at least 56 days at the same skirmish site can be registered by that site.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Retailers have access to the database to verify that the purchaser can provide them with a defence.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The Border Agency also has access to check legality of imports.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] As an alternative to RIFs, IFs (Imitation Firearms, including 'two tones') are available in the UK.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] These are RIFs which have been painted a bright colour (excluding white/silver/gold) over at least 51% of the item.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] No specific defence is required for selling an IF, although the minimum age for purchasing remains 18.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] In Canada, there are laws pertaining to airsoft importing.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] All airsoft guns that are bought in Canada are legal, but when importing it, the gun has to have between 366FPS and 500FPS to pass inspection at customs, otherwise the gun will be shipped back or destroyed.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Airsoft guns in the United States are sold with a federally mandated orange tip which must be 1/4 inch or longer covering the muzzle of the replica.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Airsoft technology is used in military training and law enforcement training.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Due to airsoft's realism, relatively safe projectiles, and economical ammunition, it is well-suited to war games and force-on-force scenarios to train and improve troop's tactical proficiency via associative learning and stress inoculation.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Multiple airsoft inventions were developed originally for military and law enforcement use.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Marking rounds were invented by Kerry T.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Bowden to allow trainees to see where each projectile landed.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Much like paintball and simunitions, these marking pellets would break upon impact, marking the target with luminescent liquid.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Unlike traditional plastic pellets, marking rounds are heavier to ensure breakage of the shell on impact.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The weight can be adjusted by adding heavier liquid.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Marking rounds are critical for trainees because they allow the shooter to see exactly where they hit the target.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] This allows them to extrapolate their mistakes and improve their aim.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Reusable grenades were improved by Scott Frank to emulate the fragmentation of a real grenade in war games and scenarios.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The grenade can be loaded with paint or pellets.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] It uses a quick release of highly pressurized gas to break the shell and quickly disperse pellets or paint in all directions.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Frank's grenade, although not the first, aimed to be as realistic and predictable as an actual grenade.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] He developed a more accurate timing mechanism and secondary safety mechanisms to prevent accidental discharge.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Both marking rounds and reusable grenades gave airsoft the edge it needed to enter into military and law enforcement training grounds.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The airsoft guns used for training differ from civilian models.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Guns manufactured for professional training are made to replicate the weight, feel and the sound of its real steel counterpart.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] In general, professional training airsoft guns are GBB models and enhanced with a weighted blowback mechanism to increase the force of the kick.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Some are AEGs and are built with a blowback mechanism.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] They are also outfitted with muzzle protectors that amplify the sound to a decibel level comparable to that of a real firearm.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] The average FPS for professional training airsoft guns is higher than civilian models.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Economically, airsoft is cheaper than simulation training.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Benjamin Kratz, Fort Jackson's battalion executive officer, said that one blank M16 round can cost as much as 32 airsoft rounds.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] Airsoft can also be used in military simulations such as in malls or prisons to add to the immersion.
[src:airsoft-pellets/airsoft] There are different event producers like MiR Tactical holding these events.
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] "Shock troop" is a loose translation of the German word ***Stoßtrupp*** (literally "thrust squad" or "push squad").
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] Assault troopers are typically organized for mobility with the intention that they will penetrate enemy defenses and attack into the enemy's vulnerable rear areas.
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] Any specialized, elite unit formed to fight an engagement via overwhelming assault (usually) would be considered shock troops, as opposed to "special forces" or commando-style units (intended mostly for covert operations).
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] However, both types of units could fight behind enemy lines, by surprise if required.
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] The Companion cavalry of Alexander the Great (356-326 BC) are described as being the first example of shock cavalry being used in Europe.
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] During the Paraguayan War (1864–1870), in which Paraguay fought against Brazil, Argentina, and Uruguay, the Paraguayans deployed shock troops (composed of a mixture of dismounted cavalry and fit men who could row and swim) armed with sabres, cutlasses, knives, bayonets, pistols, and hand grenades.
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] They attacked small fortified positions and boarded Brazilian river steamers.
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] During the First World War, many combatants faced the deadlock of trench warfare.
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] On the Western Front in 1915, the Germans formed a specialized unit called the Rohr Battalion to develop assault tactics.
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] During the Brusilov Offensive of 1916, the Russian general Aleksei Brusilov developed and implemented the idea of shock troops to attack weak points along the Austrian lines to effect a breakthrough, which the main Russian Army could then exploit.
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] The Russian Army had also formed hunter commando units in 1886 and used them in World War I to protect against ambushes, to perform reconnaissance and for low-intensity fights in no-man's-land.
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] The primary goal of these detached units was to infiltrate the enemy's lines and break their cohesion as much as possible.
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] These formations became known as *Stoßtruppen*, or shock troops, and the tactics they pioneered were the basis of post-WWI infantry tactics, such as the development of fire teams.
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] The same sort of tactical doctrine was widely espoused in British and French service in late 1917 and 1918, with variable results.
[src:airsoft-pellets/assault-troops] The British Army standard training manual for platoon tactics, SS 143, was used from February 1917 onwards and contained much of what was standard for German shock troops.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] A BB gun is a type of air gun that fires metallic spherical projectiles called **BBs** (not to be confused with similar-looking ball bearings), which are approximately the same size as BB-size lead birdshot used in shotguns (0.180 in or 4.6 mm in diameter).
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Modern BB guns usually have a smoothbore barrel of 4.5 mm (0.177 in) caliber, and use steel balls that measure 4.3–4.4 mm (0.171–0.173 in) in diameter and 0.33–0.35 g (5.1–5.4 gr) in weight, usually zinc- or copper-plated for corrosion resistance.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Some manufacturers still make the slightly larger traditional lead BBs that weigh around 0.48–0.50 g (7.4–7.7 gr), which are generally intended for use in rifled barrels (because lead is more malleable and exerts less wear on the rifling).
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The term "BB gun" is sometimes incorrectly used to refer to airsoft guns, which shoot plastic pellets (also often referred to as "BBs") that are larger (usually 6 mm or 0.24 in in diameter) but much less dense than metal BBs, and have significantly lower ballistic performance.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The term is sometimes mistakenly used to describe a pellet gun, which shoots diabolo-shaped (not spherical) lead projectiles at higher power and velocity.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The term *BB* originated from the nomenclature of the size of lead shots used in a smoothbore shotgun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Size "BB" shots were nominally 0.180 in (4.6 mm), but tended to vary considerably in size because of the loose tolerances in shotshells.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The largest shotgun pellet commonly used was named *00* or *double ought* and was used for hunting deer and thus called *buckshot*, while the smaller BB-sized shot was typically used to shoot small/medium-sized game birds and called *birdshot*.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] In 1886, the Markham Air Rifle Company in Plymouth, Michigan produced the first wooden-construct spring-piston air rifle design as a youth training gun, and used the BB lead shott as the chosen ammunition.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Two years later, the neighbouring Plymouth Air Rifle Company (later renamed Daisy Manufacturing Company in 1895) introduced the first full-metal airgun that also fired BB shots – the Daisy BB Gun, which became a very popular household name because of successful marketing.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Around 1900, Daisy changed their BB-size bore diameter to 0.175 in (4.4 mm), and began to market precision-made lead shot specifically for their BB guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] They called these "round shots", but the *BB* name was already well established, and consequently most users continued calling their guns *BB guns*, and the projectiles as *BB shots* or just *BBs*.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Subsequently, the term *BB* became generic, and is used loosely referring to any small spherical projectiles of various calibers and materials.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] This includes bearing balls often utilized by anti-personnel mines, .177 caliber lead/steel shots used by air guns, plastic round balls (such as the pellets used by airsoft guns), small marbles and many others.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] It has become ubiquitous to refer to any steel ball, such as a BB, as a "*ball bearing*".
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] However, BBs should not be confused with a ball bearing, which is a mechanical component using small internal rolling balls to reduce friction between moving parts of machines.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] BB guns can use any of the operating mechanisms used for air guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] However, because the projectile inherently has limited accuracy and short effective range, only the simpler and less expensive mechanisms are generally used for guns designed to fire only BBs.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Because the strength of the steel BB does not allow it to be swaged with the low propelling force used to accelerate it through the barrel, BBs are slightly smaller (4.3 to 4.4 mm (0.171 to 0.173 in)) than the internal diameter of the barrel (4.5 mm (0.177 in)).
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] This limits accuracy because little spin is imparted on the BB.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] It also limits range, because some of the pressurized gas used to accelerate the BB leaks around it and reduces the overall efficiency.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Since a BB will easily roll unhindered down the barrel, it is common to find guns that use a magnet in the loading mechanism to hold the BB at the rear of the barrel until it is fired.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The traditional and still most common powerplant for BB guns is the spring-piston pump, usually patterned after a lever-action rifle or a pump-action shotgun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The lever-action rifle was the first type of BB gun, and still dominates the inexpensive youth BB gun market.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The Daisy Model 25, modeled after a pump-action shotgun with a trombone pump-action mechanism, dominated the low-price, higher-performance market for over 60 years (1914–1978).
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Lever-action models generally have very low velocities, around 84 m/s (275 ft/s), a result of the weak springs used to keep cocking efforts low for use by youths.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The Daisy Model 25 typically achieved the highest velocities of its day, ranging from 114 to 145 m/s (375 to 475 ft/s).
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Multiple-pump pneumatic guns are also common.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Many pneumatic pellet guns provide the ability to use BBs as a cheaper alternative to lead shot.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Some of these guns have rifled barrels, but the slightly undersized BBs do not swage in the barrel, so the rifling does not impart a significant spin.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] These are the types of guns that will benefit most from using precision lead BB shot.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Pneumatic BB guns can also attain higher velocities than traditional spring-piston types.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The last common type of power for BB guns is compressed gas, most commonly the Powerlet cartridges.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The powerlet is a disposable metal gas cylinder containing 12 grams (185 gr) of compressed carbon dioxide, with a self-contained valve to release the CO2 which expands to propel the BB.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] These are primarily used in BB pistols, and are capable of rapid firing unlike spring-piston or pneumatic types.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] A typical CO2 BB pistol uses a spring-loaded magazine to feed BBs, and a double-action trigger mechanism to chamber a BB and cock the hammer.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] However some guns (either to stay true to the original gun or to make the trigger pull easier) do have a single-action trigger.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Either type of gun may also have blowback action, where CO2 will push the slide back in addition to firing a BB.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] When firing, the hammer strikes an internal valve linked to the CO2 source, which releases a measured amount of CO2 gas to fire the BB; this also gives it realistic recoil and muzzle report features.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Many CO2 BB guns are patterned after popular firearms such as the Colt M1911, and can be used for training as well as recreation.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Some gas-powered BB guns use a larger source of gas, and provide machine gun-like fire.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] These types, most notably the Shooting Star Tommy Gun (originally known as the Feltman) are commonly found at carnivals.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The MacGlashan BB Gun was used to train antiaircraft gunners in the United States Army Air Corps and United States Navy during World War II.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] A popular commercial model was the Larc M-19, which used 1 pound (454 g) canisters of Freon-12 refrigerant.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] These types have very simple operating mechanisms, based on a venturi pump.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The gas is released in a constant stream, and this is used to suck the BBs up into the barrel at rates as high as 3600 rounds per minute.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] BB guns can shoot faster than 60 m/s (200 ft/s), but are often less powerful than a conventional pellet airgun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Pellet airguns have the ability to fire considerably faster, even beyond 170 m/s (560 ft/s).
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Although claims are often exaggerated, a few airguns can actually fire a standard 0.177 caliber lead pellet faster than 320 m/s (1,000 ft/s), but these are generally not BB-firing guns.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] A BB with a velocity of only 45 m/s (150 ft/s) has skin-piercing capability, and a velocity reaching 60 m/s (200 ft/s) can fracture bone.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] This is potentially lethal, and this potential increases with velocity, but also rapidly decreases with distance.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The effective penetrating range of a BB gun with a muzzle velocity of 120 to 180 m/s (390 to 590 ft/s) is approximately 18 m (60 ft).
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] A person wearing jeans at this distance would not sustain serious injury.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] However, even at this distance a BB still might penetrate bare skin, and even if not, could leave a severe and painful bruise.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The maximum range of a BB gun in the 120 to 180 m/s (390 to 590 ft/s) range is 100–200 metres approximately, provided the muzzle is elevated to the optimum angle.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Steel BBs are prone to ricochet off hard surfaces such as brick, concrete, metal, or wood end grain.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Unlike lead pellets, which usually flatten and absorb energy upon impact, a BB bouncing off a hard surface can retain a large portion of its initial energy, and could easily cause serious eye damage.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Wearing eye protection is essential when shooting BBs at these materials, more so than when shooting lead pellets.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Army trained recruits in Quick Kill techniques using Daisy Model 99 BB guns to improve soldiers using their weapons in the Vietnam War from 1967 to 1973.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] The technique was developed for the Army by Bobby Lamar "Lucky" McDaniel and Mike Jennings.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] BB guns are often regulated as a typical air gun.
[src:airsoft-pellets/bb-gun] Air gun laws vary widely by local jurisdiction.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] In practice, almost all chemical compounds and materials are subject to biodegradation, the limiting element being time.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Vegetables may degrade within days, whereas some plastics can take a lot of time to degrade.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] A standard for biodegradability used by the European Union is that greater than 90% of the original material must be converted into CO2, water, and minerals by biological processes within 6 months.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Biodegradation does not apply to elements, thus heavy metal pollutants do not biodegrade.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The process of biodegradation can be divided into three stages: biodeterioration, biofragmentation, and assimilation.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Biodeterioration is sometimes described as a surface-level degradation that modifies the mechanical, physical and chemical properties of the material.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] This stage occurs when the material is exposed to abiotic factors in the outdoor environment and allows for further degradation by weakening the material's structure.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Some abiotic factors that influence these initial changes are compression (mechanical), light, temperature and chemicals in the environment.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] While biodeterioration typically occurs as the first stage of biodegradation, it can in some cases be parallel to biofragmentation.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Biofragmentation of a polymer is the lytic process in which bonds within a polymer are cleaved, generating oligomers and monomers in its place.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The steps taken to fragment these materials also differ based on the presence of oxygen in the system.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The breakdown of materials by microorganisms when oxygen is present is aerobic digestion, and the breakdown of materials when oxygen is not present is anaerobic digestion.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The main difference between these processes is that anaerobic reactions produce methane, while aerobic reactions do not (however, both reactions produce carbon dioxide, water, some type of residue, and a new biomass).
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] In addition, aerobic digestion typically occurs more rapidly than anaerobic digestion, while anaerobic digestion does a better job reducing the volume and mass of the material.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Due to anaerobic digestion's ability to reduce the volume and mass of waste materials and produce a natural gas, anaerobic digestion technology is widely used for waste management systems and as a source of local, renewable energy.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] In the assimilation stage, the resulting products from biofragmentation are then integrated into microbial cells.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Some of the products from fragmentation are easily transported within the cell by membrane carriers.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] However, others still have to undergo biotransformation reactions to yield products that can then be transported inside the cell.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Once inside the cell, the products enter catabolic pathways that either lead to the production of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) or elements of the cells structure.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] In practice, almost all chemical compounds and materials are subject to biodegradation processes.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The significance, however, is in the relative rates of such processes, such as days, weeks, years or centuries.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] A number of factors determine the rate at which this degradation of organic compounds occurs.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Factors include light, water, oxygen and temperature.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The degradation rate of many organic compounds is limited by their bioavailability, which is the rate at which a substance is absorbed into a system or made available at the site of physiological activity, as compounds must be released into solution before organisms can degrade them.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The rate of biodegradation can be measured in a number of ways.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Respirometry tests can be used for aerobic microbes.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] First one places a solid waste sample in a container with microorganisms and soil, and then aerates the mixture.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Over the course of several days, microorganisms digest the sample bit by bit and produce carbon dioxide – the resulting amount of CO2 serves as an indicator of degradation.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Biodegradability can also be measured by anaerobic microbes and the amount of methane or alloy that they are able to produce.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] It's important to note factors that affect biodegradation rates during product testing to ensure that the results produced are accurate and reliable.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Several materials will test as being biodegradable under optimal conditions in a lab for approval but these results may not reflect real world outcomes where factors are more variable.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] For example, a material may have tested as biodegrading at a high rate in the lab may not degrade at a high rate in a landfill because landfills often lack light, water, and microbial activity that are necessary for degradation to occur.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Thus, it is very important that there are standards for plastic biodegradable products, which have a large impact on the environment.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The development and use of accurate standard test methods can help ensure that all plastics that are being produced and commercialized will actually biodegrade in natural environments.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] One test that has been developed for this purpose is DINV 54900.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Recent advances have enabled real-time monitoring of polymer biodegradation using biosensors combined with machine learning, improving the accuracy of degradation assessments under varying environmental conditions.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Polycyclic aromatics are potential cancer-causing compounds that are produced by processing of petroleum and coal.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The term biodegradable plastics refers to materials that maintain their mechanical strength during practical use but break down into low-weight compounds and non-toxic byproducts after their use.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] This breakdown is made possible through an attack of microorganisms on the material, which is typically a non-water-soluble polymer.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Such materials can be obtained through chemical synthesis, fermentation by microorganisms, and from chemically modified natural products.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Plastics biodegrade at highly variable rates.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] PVC-based plumbing is selected for handling sewage because PVC resists biodegradation.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Some packaging materials on the other hand are being developed that would degrade readily upon exposure to the environment.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Examples of synthetic polymers that biodegrade quickly include polycaprolactone, other polyesters and aromatic-aliphatic esters, due to their ester bonds being susceptible to attack by water.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] A prominent example is poly-3-hydroxybutyrate, the renewably derived polylactic acid.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Others are the cellulose-based cellulose acetate and celluloid (cellulose nitrate).
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Under low oxygen conditions plastics break down more slowly.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The breakdown process can be accelerated in specially designed compost heap.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Starch-based plastics will degrade within two to four months in a home compost bin, while polylactic acid is largely undecomposed, requiring higher temperatures.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Polycaprolactone and polycaprolactone-starch composites decompose slower, but the starch content accelerates decomposition by leaving behind a porous, high surface area polycaprolactone.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] In 2016, a bacterium named *Ideonella sakaiensis* was found to biodegrade PET.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] In 2020, the PET degrading enzyme of the bacterium, PETase, has been genetically modified and combined with MHETase to break down PET faster, and also degrade PEF.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] In 2021, researchers reported that a mix of microorganisms from cow stomachs could break down three types of plastics.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Many plastic producers have gone so far even to say that their plastics are compostable, typically listing corn starch as an ingredient.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The term "composting" is often used informally to describe the biodegradation of packaging materials.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Legal definitions exist for compostability, the process that leads to compost.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] **Biodegradability**: the conversion of >90% of the original material into CO2, water and minerals by biological processes within 6 months.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] **Disintegrability**: at least 90% of the original mass should be decomposed into particles that are able to pass through a 2x2 mm sieve.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] **Quality**: absence of toxic substances and other substances that impede composting.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Biodegradable technology is established technology with some applications in product packaging, production, and medicine.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The chief barrier to widespread implementation is the trade-off between biodegradability and performance.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] For example, lactide-based plastics are inferior packaging properties in comparison to traditional materials.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Biodegradable technology is especially utilized by the bio-medical community.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Biodegradable polymers are classified into three groups: medical, ecological, and dual application, while in terms of origin they are divided into two groups: natural and synthetic.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The Clean Technology Group is exploiting the use of supercritical carbon dioxide, which under high pressure at room temperature is a solvent that can use biodegradable plastics to make polymer drug coatings.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The polymer (meaning a material composed of molecules with repeating structural units that form a long chain) is used to encapsulate a drug prior to injection in the body and is based on lactic acid, a compound normally produced in the body, and is thus able to be excreted naturally.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The coating is designed for controlled release over a period of time, reducing the number of injections required and maximizing the therapeutic benefit.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Professor Steve Howdle states that biodegradable polymers are particularly attractive for use in drug delivery, as once introduced into the body they require no retrieval or further manipulation and are degraded into soluble, non-toxic by-products.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Different polymers degrade at different rates within the body and therefore polymer selection can be tailored to achieve desired release rates.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Other biomedical applications include the use of biodegradable, elastic shape-memory polymers.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Biodegradable implant materials can now be used for minimally invasive surgical procedures through degradable thermoplastic polymers.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] These polymers are now able to change their shape with increase of temperature, causing shape memory capabilities as well as easily degradable sutures.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] As a result, implants can now fit through small incisions, doctors can easily perform complex deformations, and sutures and other material aides can naturally biodegrade after a completed surgery.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] There is no universal definition for biodegradation and there are various definitions of composting, which has led to much confusion between the terms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] They are often lumped together; however, they do not have the same meaning.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Biodegradation is the naturally occurring breakdown of materials by microorganisms such as bacteria and fungi or other biological activity.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Composting is a human-driven process in which biodegradation occurs under a specific set of circumstances.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The predominant difference between the two is that one process is naturally occurring and one is human-driven.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Biodegradable material is capable of decomposing without an oxygen source (anaerobically) into carbon dioxide, water, and biomass, but the timeline is not very specifically defined.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Similarly, compostable material breaks down into carbon dioxide, water, and biomass; however, compostable material also breaks down into inorganic compounds.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The process for composting is more specifically defined, as it is controlled by humans.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Essentially, composting is an accelerated biodegradation process due to optimized circumstances.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Additionally, the end product of composting not only returns to its previous state, but also generates and adds beneficial microorganisms to the soil called humus.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] This organic matter can be used in gardens and on farms to help grow healthier plants in the future.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Composting more consistently occurs within a shorter time frame since it is a more defined process and is expedited by human intervention.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Biodegradation can occur in different time frames under different circumstances, but is meant to occur naturally without human intervention.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Even within composting, there are different circumstances under which this can occur.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The two main types of composting are at-home versus commercial.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Both produce healthy soil to be reused – the main difference lies in what materials are able to go into the process.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] At-home composting is mostly used for food scraps and excess garden materials, such as weeds.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Commercial composting is capable of breaking down more complex plant-based products, such as corn-based plastics and larger pieces of material, like tree branches.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Commercial composting begins with a manual breakdown of the materials using a grinder or other machine to initiate the process.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Because at-home composting usually occurs on a smaller scale and does not involve large machinery, these materials would not fully decompose in at-home composting.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Furthermore, one study has compared and contrasted home and industrial composting, concluding that there are advantages and disadvantages to both.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The following studies provide examples in which composting has been defined as a subset of biodegradation in a scientific context.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The first study, "Assessment of Biodegradability of Plastics Under Simulated Composting Conditions in a Laboratory Test Setting," clearly examines composting as a set of circumstances that falls under the category of degradation.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Additionally, this next study looked at the biodegradation and composting effects of chemically and physically crosslinked polylactic acid.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Notably discussing composting and biodegrading as two distinct terms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The third and final study reviews European standardization of biodegradable and compostable material in the packaging industry, again using the terms separately.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The distinction between these terms is crucial because waste management confusion leads to improper disposal of materials by people on a daily basis.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Biodegradation technology has led to massive improvements in how we dispose of waste; there now exist trash, recycling, and compost bins in order to optimize the disposal process.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] However, if these waste streams are commonly and frequently confused, then the disposal process is not at all optimized.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Biodegradable and compostable materials have been developed to ensure more of human waste is able to breakdown and return to its previous state, or in the case of composting even add nutrients to the ground.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] When a compostable product is thrown out as opposed to composted and sent to a landfill, these inventions and efforts are wasted.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Therefore, it is important for citizens to understand the difference between these terms so that materials can be disposed of properly and efficiently.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Plastic pollution from illegal dumping poses health risks to wildlife.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Animals often mistake plastics for food, resulting in intestinal entanglement.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Slow-degrading chemicals, like polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs), nonylphenol (NP), and pesticides also found in plastics, can release into environments and subsequently also be ingested by wildlife.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] These chemicals also play a role in human health, as consumption of tainted food (in processes called biomagnification and bioaccumulation) has been linked to issues such as cancers, neurological dysfunction, and hormonal changes.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] A well-known example of biomagnification impacting health in recent times is the increased exposure to dangerously high levels of mercury in fish, which can affect sex hormones in humans.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] In efforts to remediate the damages done by slow-degrading plastics, detergents, metals, and other pollutants created by humans, economic costs have become a concern.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Marine litter in particular is notably difficult to quantify and review.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Researchers at the World Trade Institute estimate that cleanup initiatives' cost (specifically in ocean ecosystems) has hit close to thirteen billion dollars a year.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The main concern stems from marine environments, with the biggest cleanup efforts centering around garbage patches in the ocean.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The Great Pacific Garbage Patch, a garbage patch the size of Mexico, is located in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] It is estimated to be upwards of a million square miles in size.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] While the patch contains more obvious examples of litter (plastic bottles, cans, and bags), tiny microplastics are nearly impossible to clean up.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] *National Geographic* reports that even more non-biodegradable materials are finding their way into vulnerable environments – nearly thirty-eight million pieces a year.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Materials that have not degraded can also serve as shelter for invasive species, such as tube worms and barnacles.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] When the ecosystem changes in response to the invasive species, resident species and the natural balance of resources, genetic diversity, and species richness is altered.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] These factors may support local economies in way of hunting and aquaculture, which suffer in response to the change.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Similarly, coastal communities which rely heavily on ecotourism lose revenue thanks to a buildup of pollution, as their beaches or shores are no longer desirable to travelers.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The World Trade Institute also notes that the communities who often feel most of the effects of poor biodegradation are poorer countries without the means to pay for their cleanup.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] In a positive feedback loop effect, they in turn have trouble controlling their own pollution sources.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] The first known use of *biodegradable* in a biological context was in 1959 when it was employed to describe the breakdown of material into innocuous components by microorganisms.
[src:airsoft-pellets/biodegradable] Now *biodegradable* is commonly associated with environmentally friendly products that are part of the earth's innate cycles like the carbon cycle and capable of decomposing back into natural elements.
